  "prompt": "What is the time complexity for reversing a string through recursion?",
  "response": "Let's analyze the time complexity of reversing a string through recursion:\n\n```python\ndef reverse_string(s):\n    # Base case\n    if len(s) <= 1:\n        return s\n    \n    # Recursive case\n    return reverse_string(s[1:]) + s[0]\n```\n\nTime Complexity Analysis:\n1. For each recursive call, the function:\n   - Creates a substring (s[1:]) - O(k) where k is the substring length\n   - Concatenates strings - O(k)\n\n2. Number of recursive calls: n (where n is the length of the string)\n\n3. Total time complexity: O(n\u00b2)\n   - Each recursive call creates and concatenates substrings\n   - Substring creation and concatenation are O(k)\n   - Total complexity becomes quadratic: O(n * n) = O(n\u00b2)\n\nSpace Complexity:\n- Recursive call stack: O(n)\n- Additional space for substring creation: O(n)\n- Total space complexity: O(n)\n\nNote: While recursive, this approach is not efficient for large strings due to its quadratic time complexity.\n\nA more efficient approach would be using two-pointer technique or iterative reversal, which can achieve O(n) time complexity.",
